#Text=David
#Text=Pole ( bishop )
#Text=David Pole ( or Poole ) ( died 1568 ) was an English Roman Catholic churchman and jurist ; he was bishop of Peterborough from 1557 until deprived by Queen Elizabeth I .
#Text=Life
#Text=He was a fellow of All Souls ' College , Oxford , in 1520 .
#Text=He devoted himself to civil law , and graduated B. Can .
#Text=L. on 2 July 1526 and D. Can .
#Text=L. on 17 February 1527 – 1528 .
#Text=In 1529 he became an advocate in Doctors ' Commons .
#Text=He was connected with the diocese of Lichfield , where he held preferments , first under Bishop Geoffrey Blyth , and then under Bishop Rowland Lee .
#Text=He was made prebendary of Tachbrook in Lichfield Cathedral on 11 April 1531 , archdeacon of Salop in April 1536 , and archdeacon of Derby on 8 January 1543 .
#Text=He received the appointment of dean of the arches and vicar-general of the archbishop of Canterbury on 14 November 1540 .
#Text=A conscientious adherent of the Roman Catholic faith , he occupied several positions of importance during Queen Mary 's reign .

#Text=In her first year he acted as vicar-general of the bishop of Lichfield , Richard Sampson , and commissioner for the deprivation of married priests , and in his capacity of archdeacon he sat on the commission for the deprivation of Thomas Cranmer , Nicholas Ridley , and Hugh Latimer , and the restoration of Edmund Bonner and other deprived bishops .
#Text=He stood high in the favour of Cardinal Pole , said to have been a relative , who appointed him his vicar-general .
#Text=During the vacancy of the see of Lichfield on Bishop Sampson 's death in 1554 , he was appointed commissary for the diocese .
#Text=In the early part of the same year he took part in the condemnation of John Hooper and Rowland Taylor .
#Text=On 25 April 1556 he was appointed on the commission to inquire after heretics , and to proceed against them .
#Text=On the death of John Chambers , the first bishop of the newly formed diocese of Peterborough , the queen sent letters commendatory to Pope Paul IV in Pole 's favour .
#Text=He was consecrated at Chiswick on 15 August 1557 by Nicholas Heath , archbishop of York .
#Text=He shortly sanctioned the execution of John Kurde , a Protestant shoemaker , who was burnt at Northampton on 20 September 1557 . [ 1 ]
#Text=On the accession of Elizabeth , he was on the first abortive commission for the consecration of Matthew Parker as archbishop , 9 September 1559 .
#Text=In the same year he , with Bonner and two other prelates , signed Archbishop Heath 's letter of remonstrance to Elizabeth , begging her to return to the Catholic faith .
#Text=His refusal to take the oath under the act of supremacy was followed by his deprivation ; but he was treated leniently by the queen .
#Text=Allowed to live on parole in London or its suburbs , he died on one of his farms in May or June 1568 .
#Text=His property he left to his friends , and his books on law and theology to his college , All Souls ' .
#Text=Footnotes
